{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":940,"record_hash":"sha256:7a07d8413678b6c85e97d4a14301585871658299d0cc0fb3014b6715df6a5e37","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:10:18.355Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Lane B Verdict**\\n\\nPick **Render** for v1 if choosing only between Render and Railway.\\n\\nRailway is credible and a bit cheaper/fancier on volume tooling, but Render is the more boring fit for “one Rust generator owns one disk and runs jobs.” Boring wins here.\\n\\n| Need | Render | Railway |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Persistent disk | Paid [REDACTED:entropy] worker can attach a disk. Only mount path persists. | Service volumes mounted read/write at runtime. |\\n| Single-writer Git cache | Enforced: disk belongs to one service instance; no multi-instance scaling with disk. | Enforced: replicas cannot be used with volumes. |\\n| Worker shape | First-class **background worker** service, plus private/web services. | “Persistent service” can be a worker/API; less explicit, still fine. |\\n| Deploy behavior | Disk disables zero-downtime deploys. | Volume also causes small downtime because multiple active deployments cannot mount the same volume. |\\n| Backups | Automatic daily snapshots, retained at least 7 days. Whole-disk restore only. | Manual + scheduled daily/weekly/monthly backups; CoW incremental; newer feature with caveats. |\\n| Resizing | Can grow disk, cannot shrink. | Live resize on paid plans; Pro can self-serve up to 1TB. |\\n| Scaling | Vertical only with disk; shard later by repo id/service/disk. | Same. Volumes block replicas. |\\n| Cost vibe | More predictable fixed instance pricing. Disk is $0.25/GB/mo. | Lower storage price, $0.15/GB/mo, but usage-based compute is squishier. |\\n| Complexity vibe | Cleaner mental model. | Slicker dev UX, slightly more magic. |\\n\\n**My suggested path**\\n\\nUse **Render private service or web service + persistent disk** for the first Agent Trail generator.\\n\\n- If the facade is also on Render: make generator a **private service**.\\n- If the facade is elsewhere: make it a locked-down **web service** with auth.\\n- If we move to queued async jobs: use a **background worker** plus a tiny API service or queue.\\n\\nFilesystem shape stays the same:\\n\\n```text\\n/data/agent-trail/\\n  repos/github/<repo-id>/repo.git\\n  locks/github/<repo-id>.lock\\n  db/agent-trail.sqlite\\n  projections/<cache-key>.json\\n  tmp/\\n```\\n\\nI’d use Railway if we care more about cheapest/slickest early deployment and are okay with a younger volume/backup story. For a Git/GitMeta cache daemon, Render’s restrictions are exactly the restrictions we want anyway.\\n\\nSources: [Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks), [Render scaling](https://render.com/docs/scaling), [Render deploys](https://render.com/docs/deploys), [Render background workers](https://render.com/docs/background-workers), [Render pricing](https://render.com/pricing), [Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes), [Railway volume reference](https://docs.railway.com/volumes/reference), [Railway backups](https://docs.railway.com/volumes/backups), [Railway scaling](https://docs.railway.com/deployments/scaling), [Railway pricing](https://docs.railway.com/pricing/plans).\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:10:18.355Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}